First of all, I read about a review that someone found a bug in their food. The owner of Kookoo Chicken WOULD NOT admit his mistake and tried to make it the customer's fault.  I should have never gone there.  But I still went. I thought I could give it the benefit of doubt.  As a result.  I was totally disgusted by my experience in the restaurant.  So we went to Kookoo Chicken because we were right in the neighborhood.  When the four of us walked into the restaurant, only one big round table was left on a Sunday lunchtime.  The table can sit about 8 ppl max.  Four of us took up half the table. As we were looking at the menu, 4 adults with a baby in a stroller showed up.  The owner of the restaurant automatically brought those ppl to our table and ready to sit them down.  It happened without any notification or explanation.  The owner never asked us if it was okay to sit 4 complete strangers and a baby at OUR TABLE (WE CAME FIRST!!!).  The place was not a fast food joint where you expected to share a table with others.  It was a sit-down restaurant. WE ALL FELT very disrespected.  The owner was so rude and has no consideration to his customers and his business. we stood up and left without a word of argument because we definitely don't want to give business to a place like that.  We will never go back and I will make sure everyone I know aware of how the owner treated customers. SHAME ON YOU!

We drove by this restaurant purly by accident and thought to try it.  Right before we walk it, we googled the review and it was 4.5 stars so we we're like great!  We ordered the typical Hainese Chicken with Rice, Curry Fish Head Rice Noodles Soup and the ABC ice for dessert.  The rice in the Hainese chicken was AMAZING!  It was nothing we've had in other Malaysian restaurant.  If you like garlic, you are on for a treat while this rice explodes with garlic flavor.  The chicken is made perfectly with the sauce that is matched made in heaven.  You have to get the condiments tray where the chili sauce for the chicken is in there so you get more than typical tray.  It is Tangier that typical which made my mouth dance with joy.  The curry is just spicy enough to thicker than a typical soup.  It's wonderful with flavour.  The ABC shaved ice is wonderful for the hot summer weather.  It has red beans, corn kennels, jelly, peanuts and grass jelly embedded under the shaved ice.  Overall, we love the food experience and highly recommend this place and will be returning with friends and family.

New to Brooklyn, this place beats the competitors by a mile. The portion sizes are just right, which makes KKC a great place to eat alone or as a bigger group. My favorite dishes that I would definitely recommend are the Hainanese Chicken, Curry Laksa, Prawn Mee,  Bak Kut Tea (?), and the Roti Canai. The Hainanese​ chicken is perfectly tender which makes even the Chicken Breast that I usually avoid worth it. The oil rice that they have is delicious and reminds me of when I had Hainanese Chicken in Malaysia and Singapore. If you like spicy foods, you'd like the spicy sauces that come with the dishes and the kick you'll get from the Curry or Shrimp noodles. Protip: since this is a pretty authentic place, skip the pad thai and fried rice and go for the traditional Malaysian dishes. They've got good vegetarian options too for my girlfriend and she especially likes the noodle dish that combines fried and wet noodles (ordered without meat).  They get pretty busy on the weekends but the wait is totally worth it. Popping in on the weekdays is usually not a problem. The space itself is kind of small but it's clean and honestly very attractive for especially for the restaurants in the neighborhood. Since everything is open, it can get somewhat loud when it's busy but that's usually how most asian restaurants are anyway. Service wise, the waiters/waitresses don't speak as much english as ideal but they can generally understand you and are very friendly. They do speak chinese and malaysian, which is great for when I bring my family along. Lots of dishes have peanuts in it so make sure to let them know beforehand.  They're open till 10 o'clock which makes dropping by after work pretty easy. I've ordered to go from there but definitely prefer eating in the restaurant since some of the foods like the Satay is better on the spot. We usually order for family gatherings and our family friends are usually blown away by the food. It'd be great if there were more parking spaces by the area but what can you really do. Anyways, Koo Koo Chicken is a weird name but I hope this place keeps up the good work and it's overall great value and you'll get great food at affordable prices.
